post_text:
These 5th graders worked on the "Patriot Project". Last year, Mrs. Block, 4th grade teacher received a $500 grant from the Mary Chilton Daughters of the American Revolution to purchase fleece to make 50 blankets for our local veterans. This project was in partnership with the local women of the American Legion Auxiliary. The blankets have been delivered to Bethesda, Sun Dial, and Strand Kjvorsvig Nursing Homes. Additional blankets will be distributed to other local veterans in the next few weeks. Each veteran received a poem along with their blanket:
You are a valued veteran, we know it's true. You fought for America's red, white, and blue.
Your military service was years ago. Time cannot take away your honor though.
You are a patriot kind and strong. To America you've remained loyal all along.
We hope this blanket made of red, blue, and white will wrap you in a hug all through the night.
To us you are a hero true. We thank you for your service and may God bless you.

God Bless our local veterans.

post_text: Please examine carefully any special honors that you randomly get in the mail. This very legit looking award package arrived to several of our high school students today. Asking them to send in $75 to confirm membership. We don’t know how these people find your names and addresses but these junk mail awards are very common and you should never have to pay for an honor. If you are ever wondering if something is legit, please ask or do a quick google search. Here is what I found on this one https://www.collegeprepresults.com/is-nshss-national-society-of-high-school-scholars-a-scam-or-a-real-award/

post_text:
Congratulations to Olivia Dorsett of the FCCLA Chapter as she advances on to the Virtual National FCCLA Meeting! Olivia competed in Teach and Train- one of her requirements was to create a lesson that aligns with the teacher she chose to shadow earlier in the year. In the pictures attached you can see she had to use her “teacher brain” and adapt her lesson to the COVID-19 Pandemic- she rocked it! Congratulations Olivia and good luck at Nationals!

We had two other members who took on the battle of a Virtual State FCCLA meeting as well; congratulations to Sarah Sippel earning a silver medal in Repurpose and Redesign and to Brianna Duerre earning a gold medal in Fashion Construction! We are so proud of all three of you!

I have been able to step back and look at this situation in a more positive outlook. This time has allowed me to reflect on the special things in life. I have been able to spend quality time with my family before going off to college in the fall.”
We are all in this together 🧡

post_text: Parents, we understand that becoming a teacher while trying to maintain your career is not a job you asked for or feel qualified for. Our teachers are committed to maintaining learning but we also understand this process takes a lot of grace. You don’t have to do it all in one day. I love all the stories we are seeing of games, cooking lessons, art, and silliness. You are teaching your kids lessons that don’t come from a classroom. The most important thing is that you are all okay at the end of this and we will figure out how to move forward together.

PICK UP/ DROP OFF POINTS ARE READY.

Tuesday, March 24, will be the pick up and drop off of homework and other items for grades preschool through 6th grade. Teachers have been in the process of lining up times with parents. If you don’t have a time, please contact your child’s teacher. Grades 2, 3, 4 & 5 drop off will be outside the building on the sidewalk of the south end of the elementary. Grades preschool, prekindergarten, kindergarten, 1st, & 6th grade will be outside the building on the sidewalk north of the elementary gym. Parents need to place items that need to go back to their child’s teacher in the appropriate labeled tote. Teachers will have a labeled bag sitting next to the tote with items that need to go home to the student. The next drop off, pick up day will be Tuesday, March 31. This will be done on a weekly basis. Any questions, contact your teacher or elementary office. #sdkeepslearning

We ❤️ our teachers. We gave educators almost no notice. We asked them to completely redesign what school looks like. In a few hours local administrators and teachers "Apollo 13'ed" the problem and fixed it. Kids learning needs being met in the midst of a global crisis.

There is no doubt teachers are amongst the most flexible, smartest, most ingenious people in society. Our teachers miss “their kids” so much right now but I am watching in amazement at some of the innovative ways they are finding to keep learning happening.

These screenshots are of Ms. VanderVorst’s classes❤️❤️❤️ Please share with your teachers how much appreciate them ❤️❤️❤️

Dear 7-12 grade parents,

Each year our district receives federal funding (Perkins) that may be used in our Career and Technical Education programs. As a district we are required to attain data from students and parents in an effort to maintain certifications in our CTE programs and to continue to receive Perkins funds.

Please use this link to complete the parent survey (you may need to copy and paste this link in your web browser) https://forms.gle/rrXFUF3AZaVxj94u8

Hard copies are available in the HS office. Thank you.

post_text: Wonderful turnout for the American Education Week food drive for the Day County Food Pantry. All together, we gathered enough canned goods and paper products to fill about 30 + boxes. PE class helped us load and unload the foods at the Day County Food Pantry... thanks for all your help. Thank you to Susan, Becky and Brian for helping find boxes, loading and unloading the boxes at the armory too. Finally, Thank you to all of us who help the Day County Area a better place to live!

shared_text:
South Dakota FFA Foundation
July 23, 2019 at 11:20 AM ·

Cheyanne Deibert of the Webster/Waubay FFA Chapter was selected to throw out the first pitch at the Minnesota Twins game vs. the Oakland A's on Sunday July 21. Accompanying her on the field for FFA day with the Twins, were 3 Minnesota State FFA Officers. Cheyanne was able to keep the baseball, a twins cap and a Twins Jersey. The Minnesota FFA Association organized the event with the Minnesota Twins and various corporate sponsors. Cheyanne is the Webster/Waubay FFA Chapter Vice President.

Congratulations to Brianna Duerre as she represented the Webster Area FCCLA Chapter this week in Anaheim, CA. She received a GOLD on her Food Innovations Project! Ms. V, the entire Chapter and the community are so so proud of you! Your hard work and dedication does not go unnoticed.
🥇 🥇 🥇
While in Anaheim Brianna and Ms. V were able to experience several tourist attractions from Disneyland to a few beaches! On Tuesday they had the opportunity to volunteer as evaluators on two different STAR events to bring back ideas for this up coming year!

post_text: #Bearcatnation! The Bearcats showed up big time this weekend at the State track meet. Everyone had solid performances, and the boys brought home the sixth place team trophy. In girls pole vault Annie got second and Abby seventh. Jhett is the long jump state champion and high jump runner-up, Coby got third (100m), fourth (200m) and seventh (pole vault), Austin placed sixth in triple jump. Way to go Bearcats!!

post_text: Webster Area High School Academic Awards are Thursday May 2nd at 7pm. This is the evening that we get to celebrate a year full of awards and the seniors will be presented with all their scholarships. All students and parents are invited to attend. I personally feel that its one of most important events for underclassmen to be part of. Come learn about the amazing supportive community we live in and the scholarship opportunities that are available to our students.

EL Monster Effects - 1st Place
EL On Target - 1st Place
ML Escape Artists - 1st Place
EL Medical Mystery - 2nd Place and qualified for lottery to go to Globals
